docs.abstract: A partnership with Apple has made eight iPads available to every major league club that can be used in dugouts during games to consult scouting reports and other information.
docs.snippet: A partnership with Apple has made eight iPads available to every major league club that can be used in dugouts during games to consult scouting reports and other information.
docs.lead_paragraph: If a major league coach or player is scrolling through an iPad in the dugout, he is probably not perusing Facebook but rather accessing his scouting reports.

docs.lead_paragraph: The European Union’s competition authorities are poised to announce a major tax ruling against Apple’s tax dealings with the Irish government on Tuesday, a decision that will likely increase trans-Atlantic tension over how some of the world’s largest companies pay taxes on their global operations.

docs.abstract: Apple, which has been criticized for not paying outside hackers who point out bugs, says it will pay as much as $200,000 to people who flag critical vulnerabilities.
docs.snippet: Apple, which has been criticized for not paying outside hackers who point out bugs, says it will pay as much as $200,000 to people who flag critical vulnerabilities.
docs.lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — Apple, which has been criticized in recent years for failing to pay outside hackers who report bugs in its products, said on Thursday that it would begin offering a so-called bug bounty to technologists who alert the company to flaws.

headline.main: Apple Will Pay a ‘Bug Bounty’ to Hackers Who Report Flaws
headline.print_headline: Apple Will Pay Hackers to Report Vulnerabilities

docs.abstract: A blast of Takata airbag parts highlights just how risky it is to transport the propellant for the components.
docs.snippet: A blast of Takata airbag parts highlights just how risky it is to transport the propellant for the components.
docs.lead_paragraph: A woman was killed in her home and four other people were injured when a truck carrying Takata airbag parts crashed and detonated in Texas last week. The blast demonstrated just how potent the explosives used to activate Takata airbags are, creating an explosion so immense that the victim’s remains were not found for two days.

headline.main: Morning Agenda: Truck of Takata Airbag Parts Explodes, Apple Faces Taxes, Mondelez Abandons Hershey

docs.abstract: Lawmakers have criticized companies that avoid taxes by moving overseas. But they’re rallying to Apple’s defense after an E.U. demand for $14.5 billion in back taxes.
docs.snippet: Lawmakers have criticized companies that avoid taxes by moving overseas. But they’re rallying to Apple’s defense after an E.U. demand for $14.5 billion in back taxes.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — American lawmakers have for years been assailing companies for dodging taxes with overseas maneuvers. But now that the European Union has done something about it by trying to wrest billions of dollars from Apple, those officials have offered a response viewed by many as rife with hypocrisy: collective outrage.

headline.main: Yesterday, Outraged by Apple’s Tax Dodge. Today, by Its Tax Bill.
headline.print_headline: Apple, Once a Tax Outcast, Now Has Allies
